in the Western Balkans Squeezed Between Commercialization and Politicization -- tCHAPTER 14 Digital Switchover and Public Service Media in the Western Balkans -- tCHAPTER 15 Prospects for Post-Switchover Media Policy in the Western Balkan Countries -- tCHAPTER 16 State of the Art and the Future of Public Service Media in the Western Balkans -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe agenda for transition after the demise of communism in the Western Balkans made the conversion of state radio and television into public service broadcasters a priority, converting mouthpieces of the regime into public forums in which various interests and standpoints could be shared and deliberated. There is general agreement that this endeavor has not been a success. Formally, the countries adopted the legal and institutional requirements of public service media according to European standards. The ruling political elites, however, retained their control over the public media by various means. Can this trend be reversed? Instead of being marginalized or totally manipulated, can public service media become vehicles of genuine democratization?  A comparison of public service media in seven countries (Albania, Bosnia & Herzegovina, Croatia, Kosovo, Montenegro, North Macedonia, and Serbia) addresses these important questions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszBalkan Peninsula. 0aPublic broadcastingzBalkan Peninsula. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  a21st century, Democratization, European Union, Media regulation, Regime change, Postcommunism.1 aAhmetašević, Nidžara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBajomi-Lázár, Péter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc